04 | College Park, MD | #1 Maryland | 11 | #10 Virginia | 2\n| 2004 | Chapel Hill, NC | #3 Maryland | 12 | #14 Virginia | 11\n| 2005 | Charlottesville, VA | #3 Virginia | 10 | #4 Maryland | 2\n| 2005 | Baltimore, MD | #10 Maryland | 8 | #3 Virginia | 7\n| 2006 | College Park, MD | #1 Virginia | 15 | #3 Maryland | 5\n| 2006 | Baltimore, MD | #1 Virginia | 11 | #3 Maryland | 5\n| 2007 | Charlottesville, VA | #3 Virginia | 12 | #10 Maryland | 8\n| 2007 | Durham, NC | #3 Virginia | 11 | #8 Maryland | 10\n| 2008 | College Park, MD | #4 Maryland | 13 | #1 Virginia | 7\n| 2008 | College Park, MD | #3 Virginia | 11 | #8 Maryland | 8\n| [[2008 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|2008]] | [[Annapolis, MD]] | #2 Virginia | 9 | #8 Maryland | 8<sup>OT</sup>\n| 2009 | Charlottesville, VA | #1 Virginia | 10 | #9 Maryland | 9<sup>7OT</sup>\n| 2010 | College Park, MD | #1 Virginia | 11 | #4 Maryland | 10\n| 2010 | College Park, MD | #2 Virginia | 10 | #5 Maryland | 6\n| 2011 | Charlottesville, VA | #10 Maryland | 12 | #6 Virginia | 7\n| [[2011 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|2011]] | Baltimore, MD | #10 Virginia | 9 | #8 Maryland | 7\n| 2012 | College Park, MD | #3 Virginia | 12 | #9 Maryland | 8\n| 2013 | Charlottesville, VA | #2 Maryland | 9 | #17 Virginia | 7\n| 2013 | Chapel Hill, NC | Virginia | 13 | #3 Maryland | 6\n| 2014 | College Park, MD | #4 Maryland | 9 | #8 Virginia | 6\n| [[2019 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|2019]] | [[Hempstead, NY]] | #4 Virginia | 13 | #6 Maryland | 12<sup>OT</sup>\n| note = Source:<ref name=\"results\">{{cite web|title=Maryland Men\u2019s Lacrosse Record Book|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/umterps.com/documents/2019/8/7/Record_Book.pdf]]|accessdate=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{University of Maryland, College Park}}\n{{University of Virginia}}\n{{Atlantic Coast Conference men's lacrosse navbox}}\n{{Big Ten Conference men's lacrosse navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maryland-Virginia rivalry}}\n[[Category:College lacrosse rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:Maryland Terrapins rivalries]]\n[[Category:Maryland Terrapins men's lacrosse]]\n[[Category:Virginia Cavaliers men's lacrosse]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| wide                  = yes\n| name                  = Maryland\u2013Virginia lacrosse rivalry\n| team1                 = [[Maryland Terrapins men's lacrosse|Maryland Terrapins]]\n| team1logo = Maryland Terrapins logo.svg\n| team2                 = [[Virginia Cavaliers men's lacrosse|Virginia Cavaliers]]\n| team2logo             = Virginia_Cavaliers_text_logo.svg\n| firstmeeting          = April 24, 1926<br />Maryland 10, Virginia 1\n| mostrecent            = May 18, 2019<br />Virginia 13, Maryland 12<sup>OT</sup>\n| nextmeeting           = \n| total                 = 92\n| series                = Maryland leads, 47\u201345\n| largestvictory        = Maryland, 22\u20133 (1929)\n| longeststreak         = Maryland, 8 (1926\u20131952, 1954\u20131961)\n| currentstreak         = Virginia, 1 (2019\u2013Present)\n}}\nThe '''Maryland\u2013Virginia lacrosse rivalry''' is an [[college lacrosse|intercollegiate lacrosse]] rivalry between the [[Maryland Terrapins men's lacrosse|Maryland Terrapins]] and [[Virginia Cavaliers men's lacrosse|Virginia Cavaliers]]. The teams first met in 1926 and have met 92 times. The two are some of the most historically successful intercollegiate programs, combining for 20 national titles, nine of which have come in the [[NCAA]] era. The Terps and Cavaliers were league foes in the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] from 1954 to 2014, before Maryland joined the [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] the following year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Svrluga|first=Barry|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/maryland-joins-big-ten-leaving-acc/2012/11/19/e24531dc-3268-11e2-9cfa-e41bac906cc9_story.html|title=Big Ten Expansion: Maryland leaves ACC, joins conference in financial move|date=2012-11-19|work=Washington Post|access-date=2020-04-08|last2=Prewitt|first2=and Alex|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/washington/ncaa/marylands-move-big-ten-was-no-brainer|title=Maryland's move to the Big Ten was a no brainer|date=2012-11-19|website=NBC Sports Washington|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The teams ceased their annual matchup until a meeting five years later in the [[2019 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship]]. Maryland leads the series 47\u201345 through 2020.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://umterps.com/documents/2019/8/7/Record_Book.pdf|title=Record Book (PDF)|website=University of Maryland Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> \n\n== Series History ==\n\n=== Maryland Preeminence (1926 to 1970) ===\nThe series was dominated by Maryland early on, with each of the first four meetings being no closer than nine goals. After five games in six years, the series would go on an 18-year hiatus before resuming as an annual fixture in 1950. Virginia grabbed its victory in nine tries with a five goal win in [[College Park, Maryland|College Park]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://virginiasports.com/documents/2019/5/29/alltimeresults.pdf?id=6406|title=All Time Results 2020 (PDF)|website=University of Virginia Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> \n\nThe following year, the teams would meet in 1954 as conference foes for the first time. Maryland continued its early series dominance in response to its first series loss by reeling off another eight consecutive victories. Virginia would snap that streak with its first home victory in 1962, before closing the decade with its first victory in College Park since 1953 in a 9\u20137 win.<ref name=\":1\" /> A victory the following year would be the final before the advent of the [[NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship]]. At the end of this era, Maryland would hold a commanding 21 to 5 series lead, punctuated by its eight game winning streaks.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe advent of the NCAA tournament and rise of Virginia as a major lacrosse power led to a hotly contested period in the series's history. However, the Terps would win the final five meetings of the 1970s, including their first meeting in the postseason, a 15 to 10 victory in the [[1978 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|1978 quarterfinals]].\n\n=== Virginian Dominance (1980s to Present) ===\nVirginia would grab the initiative in 1980, winning seven of the next eight, though Maryland would again top the Cavaliers in the [[1983 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|1983 quarterfinals]]. Since 1980, the Cavs have won 37 of 55 meetings to narrow Maryland's series lead to just two games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://virginiasports.com/news/2019/5/16/mens-lacrosse-no-4-uva-and-no-6-maryland-rekindle-rivalry-on-saturday-in-the-ncaa-quarterfinals.aspx|title=No. 4 UVA and No. 6 Maryland Rekindle Rivalry on Saturday in the NCAA Quarterfinals|website=University of Virginia Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Nonetheless, the meetings have often been between top five ranked teams and have lead to numerous classic games. One of the most significant was the sole meeting in 2009, the longest lacrosse game in NCAA history.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://umterps.com/news/2009/3/28/207292926.aspx|title=No. 9 Terps Men's Lacrosse Drop Longest Game In NCAA History at No. 1 Virginia|website=University of Maryland Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> An unintentional whistle by the officiating staff negated what would have been a game-winning goal by Terrapins attackman [[Grant Catalino]] in the first overtime.<ref name=\":3\" /> After seven overtime periods, the Cavaliers finally put away Maryland with the game-winning tenth goal to prevail 10\u20139, and preserved its perfect record, 11\u20130.<ref name=\":3\" /> The game would ultimately be the determinant in the ACC regular season championship, as the Terrapins' loss tied them with Virginia in a split title.\n\nWith the advent of the ACC postseason lacrosse tournament in 1989, the two teams would meet even more frequently. The programs would meet 14 times in the ACC postseason, with UVA holding a 8\u20136 lead in these games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://virginiasports.com/documents/2019/5/29/ACCTournamentHistory.pdf?id=6408|title=https://virginiasports.com/documents/2019/5/29/ACCTournamentHistory.pdf?id=6408|website=University of Virginia Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> In the NCAA tournament, the Cavaliers hold the series lead at four victories to three, winning each of the last four matchups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://virginiasports.com/documents/2019/5/29/NCAATournamentHistory.pdf?id=6413|title=https://virginiasports.com/documents/2019/5/29/NCAATournamentHistory.pdf?id=6413|website=University of Virginia Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The most significant NCAA meeting occurred in the 2011, as Virginia downed the Terps in the title game by two goals to win their fifth NCAA championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/college/lacrosse/bs-sp-ncaa-lacrosse-final-0531-20110530-story.html|title=Maryland men's bid for NCAA title ends with 9-7 loss to Virginia in final|last=Sun|first=Edward Lee, The Baltimore|website=baltimoresun.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.streakingthelawn.com/2019/5/17/18629181/ncaa-tournament-lacrosse-mens-virginia-cavaliers-maryland-terrapins-quarterfinals|title=NCAA Tournament: Virginia and Maryland renew dormant rivalry|last=Darney|first=Caroline|date=2019-05-17|website=Streaking The Lawn|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Terps departed the ACC for the Big Ten, they would not play the Cavs again until the [[2019 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|2019]] edition of the NCAA tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://virginiasports.com/news/2019/5/18/mens-lacrosse-no-3-seeded-uva-advances-to-championship-weekend-with-overtime-win-over-maryland.aspx|title=No. 3 seeded UVA Advances to Championship Weekend with Overtime Win Over Maryland|website=University of Virginia Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Old sentiments stirred again in a controversial Virginia victory in the quarters. While Maryland controlled much of the match and held a commanding five goal lead at one point, the Cavaliers rallied in the fourth quarter, helped by a critical call that attackman Michael Kraus' shot was deemed a score despite clanging off the post.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dbknews.com/2019/05/18/maryland-mens-lacrosse-virginia-game-score-recap-result-ncaa-tournament-jared-bernhardt/|title=Maryland men\u2019s lacrosse falls in OT to Virginia, 13-12, after blowing five-goal lead - The Diamondback|last=Myers|first=Eric|website=www.dbknews.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Virginia took the opening faceoff in overtime, and Matt Moore scored 45 seconds later to propel the Cavaliers into the semifinal and end the Terps\u2019 season short of the final four for the first time since 2013.<ref name=\":0\" /> UVA would ultimately defeat [[Yale Bulldogs men's lacrosse|Yale]] in the final to win their eighth national championship. In 2020, the teams were scheduled to resume the rivalry with a regular season matchup<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dbknews.com/2019/12/18/maryland-mens-lacrosse-releases-2020-schedule-ncaa-champion-virginia-john-tillman/|title=Maryland men\u2019s lacrosse releases 2020 schedule, will face reigning NCAA champion Virginia - The Diamondback|last=Suggs|first=David|website=www.dbknews.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> that was ultimately cancelled as a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dbknews.com/2020/03/12/big-ten-cancels-all-spring-sports-coronavirus-maryland-athletics/|title=Big Ten cancels all spring sports due to coronavirus - The Diamondback|last=Kostka|first=Andy|website=dbknews.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Rival Accomplishments==\nThe following summarizes the accomplishments of the two programs.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Team !! Maryland Terrapins !! Virginia Cavaliers\n|-\n| Pre-NCAA National Titles || style={{NCAA color cell|Maryland Terrapins}}|9 || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Virginia Cavaliers}}\" |2\n|-\n| [[NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|NCAA National Titles]] || style={{NCAA color cell|Maryland Terrapins}}|3<!-- As of the 2020 season --> || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Virginia Cavaliers}}\" |6<!-- As of the 2020 season -->\n|-\n| [[NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship appearances by school|NCAA Final Four Appearances]] || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Maryland Terrapins}}\"|26<!-- As of the 2019-20 season --> || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Virginia Cavaliers}}\" |23<!-- As of the 2019-20 season -->\n|-\n| [[NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship appearances by school|NCAA Tournament Appearances]] || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Maryland Terrapins}}\"|42<!-- As of the 2020 season --> || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Virginia Cavaliers}}\" |39<!-- As of the 2020 season -->\n|-\n| [[NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship all-time team records|NCAA Tournament Record]] || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Maryland Terrapins}}\"|63\u201339<!-- As of the 2020 season --> || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Virginia Cavaliers}}\" |51\u201333<!-- As of the 2020 season -->\n|-\n| Conference Tournament Titles || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Maryland Terrapins}}\"|6<!-- As of the 2020 season --> || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Virginia Cavaliers}}\" |7<!-- As of the 2020 season -->\n|-\n| Conference Championships || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Maryland Terrapins}}\"|35<!-- As of the 2020 season --> || style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Virginia Cavaliers}}\" |25<!-- As of the 2020 season -->\n|-\n| [[Tewaaraton Award|Tewaarton Award Recipients]]|| style