       = \n| steering           = \n<!-- Missiles only -->\n| wingspan           = \n| propellant         = \n| ceiling            = \n| altitude           = \n| boost              = \n| depth              = \n| accuracy           = \n| launch_platform    = \n| transport          =\n<!-- For all -->\n| ref                = \n}}\n\n'''MAM-L/C''' ('''Mikro Ak\u0131ll\u0131 M\u00fchimmat''', Smart Micro Munition) is a  [[laser-guided]] [[smart munition]] system under production by Turkish defence industry manufacturer [[Roketsan]]. MAM has been developed for [[unmanned aerial vehicles]] (UAV), light attack aircraft and air-ground missions for low payload capacity air platforms. Roketsan claims MAM can engage both stationary and moving targets with high precision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asianmilitaryreview.com/2019/03/roketsans-smart-micro-guided-munitions-boost-effectiveness-of-uavs/|title=Roketsan\u2019s Smart Micro Guided Munitions Boost Effectiveness of UAVs|last=Review|first=Asian Military|date=2019-03-25|website=Asian Military Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenceturkey.com/en/content/mam-l-boosts-effectiveness-of-uavs-2846|title=MAM-L Boosts Effectiveness of UAVs - Defence Turkey Magazine|website=www.defenceturkey.com|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gbp.com.sg/stories/roketsans-smart-micro-munition-continues-to-prove-itself/|title=Roketsan's Smart Micro Munition Product Family|website=Global Business Press {{!}} GBP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n\n==Versions==\n*MAM-C-[[High explosive]] variant<ref name=\"urlMAM-C SMART MICRO MUNITION \u2013 Roketsan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.roketsan.com.tr/en/product/mam-c-smart-micro-munition/ |title=MAM-C SMART MICRO MUNITION \u2013 Roketsan |format= |work= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n*MAM-L-[[Thermobaric]] variant\n\n== Technical specifications ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Diameter\n|160 mm\n|-\n|Length\n|1 m\n|-\n|Weight\n|22 kg\n|-\n|Range\n|8 km (14 km with Inertial Navigation System/Global Positioning System Option)\n|-\n|Seeker\n|Semi-Active Laser Seeker\n|-\n|Warhead Types\n|\n* Tandem Effective Against Reactive Armor\n* High-Explosive Blast Fragmentation\n* Thermobaric\n* Anti-Tank Warhead\n|-\n|Fuse\n|\n* Impact\n* Proximity\n|-\n|Platforms\n|Unmanned aerial vehicles and light attack aircraft.\n|-\n| colspan=2 |<small>Source: Roketsan A.\u015e.</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roketsan.com.tr/en/product/mam-l-smart-micro-munition/|title=MAM-L Smart Micro Munition \u2013 Roketsan|website=www.roketsan.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== Operational history ==\n[[File:Roketsan MAM-L - IDET 2017.JPG|thumb|The Smart Micro Munition (MAM-L)]]\nOperations in which the rocket is used,\n\n* [[Operation Euphrates Shield]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://setav.org/en/assets/uploads/2017/11/R97_Euphrates.pdf|title=OES operation diary|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [[Operation Olive Branch]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/analysis-news/military-scorecard-of-operation-olive-branch/1099535|title=Military scorecard of Operation Olive Branch|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n* EFES 2018 Exercises<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.idef.com.tr//en|title=EFES Exercise|website=www.idef.com.tr|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n* [[Operation Claw (2019)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/turkey/operation-claw-3-launched-in-northern-iraq-turkey/1563672|title=Operation Claw 3 launched in northern Iraq: Turkey|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n\n* [[Operation Peace Spring]] 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://investigativejournal.org/pkk-spokesman-on-turkeys-operation-peace-spring/|title=PKK Spokesman on Turkey's Operation \u201cPeace Spring\u201d|last=Snell|first=Lindsey|date=2019-11-15|website=The Investigative Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n* [[Operation Spring Shield]] 2020<ref name=\"Roblin 2020\">{{cite web | last=Roblin | first=Sebastien | title=Turkish Drones and Artillery Are Devastating Assad\u2019s Forces In Idlib Province-Here\u2019s Why | website=Forbes | date=2020-03-02 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/sebastienroblin/2020/03/02/idlib-onslaught-turkish-drones-artillery-and-f-16s-just-destroyed-over-100-armored-vehicles-in-syria-and-downed-two-jets/ | access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Mountable vehicles ==\n[[File:TAI Anka Teknofest2019 (1).jpg|thumb|TAI Anka loaded with MAM-L]]\n\n*[[Bayraktar Tactical UAS]]\n*[[Bayraktar TB2]]\n*[[Bayraktar Ak\u0131nc\u0131]]\n*[[TAI Aksungur]]\n*[[TAI Anka]]\n*[[Vestel Karayel]]\n*[[TAI H\u00fcrku\u015f]] ( [[Trainer (aircraft)|basic trainer]] and [[ground attack aircraft]] for the [[Turkish Armed Forces]].)[[File:Bayraktar TB2 Ground.jpg|thumb|Bayraktar TB2 loaded with MAM L]]\n\n<br />\n== See also ==\n* [[Roketsan Cirit]]\n* [[Turkish Aerospace Industries]]\n* [[ROKETSAN]]\n* [[ASELSAN]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Turkey]]\n[[Category:Rockets and missiles]]\n[[Category:Unmanned aerial vehicle manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Turkish military aircraft]]\n\n{{Turkish Army equipment}}\n", "name_user": "Estin Gi\u00e7 Gi\u00e7", "label": "safe", "comment": "L/C it's versions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MAM_(Smart_Micro_Munition)"}
{"title_page": "Haustr\u00f6kkri\u00f0 yfir m\u00e9r", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| italic title   = \n| name           = Haustr\u00f6kkri\u00f0 yfir m\u00e9r\n| image          = File:Haustr\u00f6kkri\u00f0YfirM\u00e9r.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = First edition\n| author         = [[Snorri Hjartarson]]\n| audio_read_by  = \n| title_orig     = \n| orig_lang_code = \n| title_working  = \n| translator     = \n| illustrator    = \n| cover_artist   = \n| country        = [[Iceland]]\n| language       = [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]]\n| series         = \n| release_number = \n| subject        = \n| genre          = [[poetry]]\n| set_in         = \n| published      = [[1979 in literature|1979]]\n| publisher      = [[M\u00e1l og Menning]]\n| publisher2     = \n| pub_date       = \n| english_pub_date = \n| media_type     = \n| pages          = \n| awards         = [[Nordic Council's Literature Prize]] of 1981\n| isbn           = \n| oclc           = \n| dewey          = \n| congress       = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n| native_wikisource = \n| wikisource     = \n| notes          =\n| exclude_cover  = \n}}\n'''''Haustr\u00f6kkri\u00f0 yfir m\u00e9r''''' is a 1979 poetry collection by Icelandic poet [[Snorri Hjartarson]]. It won the [[Nordic Council's Literature Prize]] in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.norden.org/en/nordic-council/nordic-council-prizes/nordisk-raads-litteraturpris/media/literature-prizewinners-1962-2013 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-12-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319235454/http://www.norden.org/en/nordic-council/nordic-council-prizes/nordisk-raads-litteraturpris/media/literature-prizewinners-1962-2013/ |archive-date=2016-03-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Nordic Council's Literature Prize}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haustrokkrid yfir mer}}\n[[Category:1979 poetry books]]\n[[Category:Icelandic poetry]]\n[[Category:Nordic Council's Literature Prize-winning works]]\n[[Category:Poetry collections]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| italic title   = \n| name           = Haustr\u00f6kkri\u00f0 yfir m\u00e9r\n| image          = File:Haustr\u00f6kkri\u00f0YfirM\u00e9r.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = First edition\n| author         = [[Snorri Hjartarson]]\n| audio_read_by  = \n| title_orig     = \n| orig_lang_code = \n| title_working  = \n| translator     = \n| illustrator    = \n| cover_artist   = \n| country        = [[Iceland]]\n| language       = [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]]\n| series         = \n| release_number = \n| subject        = \n| genre          = [[poetry]]\n| set_in         = \n| published      = [[1979 in literature|1979]]\n| publisher      = [[M\u00e1l og Menning]]\n| publisher2     = \n| pub_date       = \n| english_pub_date = \n| media_type     = \n| pages          = \n| awards         = [[Nordic Council's Literature Prize]] of 1981\n| isbn           = \n| oclc           = \n| dewey          = \n| congress       = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n| native_wikisource = \n| wikisource     = \n| notes          =\n| exclude_cover  = \n}}\n'''''Haustr\u00f6kkri\u00f0 yfir m\u00e9r''''' is a 1979 poetry collection by Icelandic poet [[Snorri Hjartarson]]. It won the [[Nordic Council's Literature Prize]] in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.norden.org/en/nordic-council/nordic-council-prizes/nordisk-raads-litteraturpris/media/literature-prizewinners-1962-2013 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-12-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319235454/http://www.norden.org/en/nordic-council/nordic-council-prizes/nordisk-raads-litteraturpris/media/literature-prizewinners-1962-2013/ |archive-date=2016-03-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Nordic Council's Literature Prize}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haustrokkrid yfir mer}}\n[[Category:1979 books]]\n[[Category:Icelandic poetry]]\n[[Category:Nordic Council's Literature Prize-winning works]]\n[[Category:Poetry collections]]\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1979 bookstoCategory:1979 poetry booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haustr%C3%B6kkri%C3%B0_yfir_m%C3%A9r"}
{"title_page": "Kelly Sutherland (chuckwagon)", "text_new": "{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Kelly Sutherland\n| image             =\n \n| image_size        = <!-- defaults to 180px unless a value is entered -->\n| caption           = \n| nationality       = Canadian\n| birth_name        = <!-- Only if different from name -->\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1951|10|29}}\n| birth_place       = \n| related to        = <!-- list of notable relatives with line breaks --> \n| current series    = [[World Professional Chuckwagon Association|WPCA]]\n| first year        = 1969\n| current team      = \n| car number        = <!-- if known -->\n| engine            =\n| crew chief        =\n| spotter           = <!-- Note: \"spotter\" and \"codriver\" share a field     -->\n| codriver          = <!-- If both are specified, \"spotter\" will be displayed -->\n| former teams      = \n| starts            = \n| WPCA world championships     = 12 (1974, 1977, 1979, 1982, 1983, 1996, 1998, 1999, 2006, 2007, 2010, 2011)\n| Calgary Stampede             = 12 (1974, 1975, 1977, 1978, 1986, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2001, 2002, 2010, 2011\n| podiums           =\n| poles             = \n| fastest laps      = <!-- if known -->\n| best finish       = <!-- if a final championship placing has been recorded -->\n| year              = <!-- use piped link if season article exists -->\n| last finish       =\n| prev series       = <!-- previous series with line breaks -->\n| prev series years = \n| titles            = \n| title years       = \n| awards            = \n| award years       = \n| updated           = \n| medaltemplates    = \n}}\n'''Kelly Sutherland''', nicknamed \"The King\",<ref name=\"Blog\">{{cite web|title=Long Live \"the King\": Kelly Sutherland is retiring from Racing|url=http://www.calgarystampede.com/blog/2017/06/05/long-live-the-king-kelly-sutherland-retires-from-racing/|website=Calgary Stampede - Blog|publisher=www.calgarystampede.com|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> (born October 29, 1951) is a professional rodeo competitor in [[chuckwagon racing]]. He is a 12-time world champion of the [[World Professional Chuckwagon Association]] and 12-time winner at the [[Calgary Stampede]].<ref name=wpca>{{cite web | url=http://www.wpca.com/profile_detail.aspx?ID=44 | title=Profile: Kelly Sutherland | work=World Professional Chuckwagon Association | accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nSutherland is from [[Grande Prairie, Alberta]].<ref name=\"wpca\" /> Chuckwagon racing is a family affair. Sutherland was inspired by his father, who was an amateur racer and other members of the family who competed.<ref name=\"Retires\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.calgarystampede.com/blog/2017/06/05/long-live-the-king-kelly-sutherland-retires-from-racing/|title=Long Live \"the King\": Kelly Sutherland is retiring from Racing|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nHe has been competing in chuckwagon racing since 1967.<ref name=\"wpca\" /> Sutherland was 14 when he started racing. He was 22 when he won his first race. He can recall being on stage for the first time for an audience of 40,000. \"When you're in the sport, you only dream about getting the opportunity to win and I was fortunate when I was young.\"<ref name=\"AlsoRetires\">{{cite web |title=Legendary chuckwagon driver Kelly Sutherland retires after 50 years |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/kelly-sutherland-chuckwagon-race-retires-1.4256724 |website=CBC News |accessdate=December 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was an outrider for the first year, then began driving in 1968. His rookie season in the WPCA was 1969.<ref name=\"wpca\" /> He competed in the 2016 Calgary Stampede Rangeland Derby.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cs.calgarystampede.com/events/gmc-rangeland-derby/results?file=2016/DriverResults-2016.htm#Kelly | title=Results (2016 Driver Results, Kelly Sutherland) | work=Calgary Stampede | accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite news | url=https://calgaryherald.com/sports/Kelly+Sutherland+continues+defy+Rangeland+Derby/10002461/story.html | title=Kelly Sutherland continues to defy age at the Rangeland Derby | work=[[Calgary Herald]] | first=Laurence | last=Heinen | date=July 5, 2014 | quote=Sutherland doesn't have many more shots to win another title before he turns 65, after which time he's no longer eligible to compete in the Rangeland Derby.}}</ref>  In 2010, Sutherland won the chuckwagon championship for the 11th time, breaking the world record. He was almost 60 years old when he won his final and 12th world championship. He also has a dozen championships from the Calgary Stampede, nine championships from the Ponoka Stampede, and one from his hometown of [[Grande Prairie]].<ref name=\"AlsoRetires\" /> He won his 12th and final world championship not long before his birthday in 2017. The year 2017 was his last year competing, as the event has a mandatory retirement age of 65.<ref name=\":2\" /> Sutherland competed in his last race in Rocky Mountain House in west central Alberta. Sutherland spent 50 years guiding horses around the track.<ref name=\"AlsoRetires\" />\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2012 Calgary Stampede [[Guy Weadick]] Award<ref>{{cite web |title=Guy Weadick Award Winners |url=https://www.calgarystampede.com/heritage/guy-weadick-award |website=Calgary Stampede |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n* 12 Calgary Stampede Championships\n* 12 World Championships\n* 7 time Calgary Stampede Aggregate Winner\n* 77 Champion final heats on World Professional Chuckwagon Association Circuit\n* 25 Victories in Championship heats on the World Professional Chuckwagon Association Circuit\n* $300,000 highest bid chuckwagon canvas sold at Calgary Stampede Canvas Auction (2012)\n<small>Source</small>:<ref name=\"Retires\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Alberta Sports Hall of Fame |title=Join us as we welcome the Class of 2020 |url=https://www.todayville.com/join-us-as-we-welcome-the-class-of-2020/ |website=todayville Red Deer |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSutherland owned a country bar in Canada in the 1980s, called Kelly's Bar at the Sutherland Inn, in Clairmont, Alberta.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jepson|first1=Tim|last2=Lee|first2=Phil|last3=Smith|first3=Tania|last4=Williams|first4=Christian|title=The Rough Guide to Canada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=92iMgE8GYQ4C&pg=PA637&lpg=PA637&dq=Kelly%27s+Bar+Clairmont+Alberta.&source=bl&ots=ubtZ70ubkU&sig=jYodKFzBZLx-CjtVoCoRz2kwncA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwitoa2czbHUAhUJLmMKHVbAD-8Q6AEIajAG#v=onepage&q=Kelly%27s%20Bar%20Clairmont%20Alberta.&f=false|website=books.google.com|publisher=Rough Guides|accessdate=9 June 2017|language=en|date=2004}}</ref> His first Chuckwagon hung from the ceiling above the dance floor.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} Sutherland's wife Debbie has been riding with him ever since he began racing competitively.<ref name=\"Retires\" />\n\nIn 2009, Sutherland participated in the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] as one of 13 torchbearers for his home town of Grand Prairie, Alberta.  Each of the torchbearers rode down the main street of the town for the one-kilometre ride with the torch. He revealed that he will put the used torch on display with his 38 chuckwagon trophies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Carrying the Olympic Torch: Day 8 \u2014 Yellowknife to Cold Lake|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/staff-blogs/carrying-the-olympic-torch-day-8-yellowknife-to-cold-lake|website=Vancouver Sun|publisher=www.vancouversun.|accessdate=January 13, 2018|date=7 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sutherland, Kelly}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Rodeo in Canada]]\n[[Category:Rodeo performers]]\n[[Category:People from Grande Prairie]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Kelly Sutherland\n| image             =\n \n| image_size        = <!-- defaults to 180px unless a value is entered -->\n| caption           = \n| nationality       = Canadian\n| birth_name        = <!-- Only if different from name -->\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1951|10|29}}\n| birth_place       = \n| related to        = <!-- list of notable relatives with line breaks --> \n| current series    = [[World Professional Chuckwagon Association|WPCA]]\n| first year        = 1969\n| current team      = \n| car number        = <!-- if known -->\n| engine            =\n| crew chief        =\n| spotter           = <!-- Note: \"spotter\" and \"codriver\" share a field     -->\n| codriver          = <!-- If both are specified, \"spotter\" will be displayed -->\n| former teams      = \n| starts            = \n| WPCA world championships     = 12 (1974, 1977, 1979, 1982, 1983, 1996, 1998, 1999, 2006, 2007, 2010, 2011)\n| Calgary Stampede             = 12 (1974, 1975, 1977, 1978, 1986, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2001, 2002, 2010, 2011\n| podiums           =\n| poles             = \n| fastest laps      = <!-- if known -->\n| best finish       = <!-- if a final championship placing has been recorded -->\n| year              = <!-- use piped link if season article exists -->\n| last finish       =\n| prev series       = <!-- previous series with line breaks -->\n| prev series years = \n| titles            = \n| title years       = \n| awards            = \n| award years       = \n| updated           = \n| medaltemplates    = \n}}\n'''Kelly Sutherland''', nicknamed \"The King\",<ref name=\"Blog\">{{cite web|title=Long Live \"the King\": Kelly Sutherland is retiring from Racing|url=http://www.calgarystampede.com/blog/2017/06/05/long-live-the-king-kelly-sutherland-retires-from-racing/|website=Calgary Stampede - Blog|publisher=www.calgarystampede.com|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> (born October 29, 1951) is a professional rodeo competitor in [[chuckwagon racing]]. He is a 12-time world champion of the [[World Professional Chuckwagon Association]] and 12-time winner at the [[Calgary Stampede]].<ref name=wpca>{{cite web | url=http://www.wpca.com/profile_detail.aspx?ID=44 | title=Profile: Kelly Sutherland | work=World Professional Chuckwagon Association | accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nSutherland is from [[Grande Prairie, Alberta]].<ref name=\"wpca\" /> Chuckwagon racing is a family affair. Sutherland was inspired by his father, who was an amateur racer and other members of the family who competed.<ref name=\"Retires\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.calgarystampede.com/blog/2017/06/05/long-live-the-king-kelly-sutherland-retires-from-racing/|title=Long Live \"the King\": Kelly Sutherland is retiring from Racing|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nHe has been competing in chuckwagon racing since 1967.<ref name=\"wpca\" /> Sutherland was 14 when he started racing. He was 22 when he won his first race. He can recall being on stage for the first time for an audience of 40,000. \"When you're in the sport, you only dream about getting the opportunity to win and I was fortunate when I was young.\"<ref name=\"AlsoRetires\">{{cite web |title=Legendary chuckwagon driver Kelly Sutherland retires after 50 years |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/kelly-sutherland-chuckwagon-race-retires-1.4256724 |website=CBC News |accessdate=December 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was an outrider for the first year, then began driving in 1968. His rookie season in the WPCA was 1969.<ref name=\"wpca\" /> He competed in the 2016 Calgary Stampede Rangeland Derby.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cs.calgarystampede.com/events/gmc-rangeland-derby/results?file=2016/DriverResults-2016.htm#Kelly | title=Results (2016 Driver Results, Kelly Sutherland) | work=Calgary Stampede | accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite news | url=https://calgaryherald.com/sports/Kelly+Sutherland+continues+defy+Rangeland+Derby/10002461/story.html | title=Kelly Sutherland continues to defy age at the Rangeland Derby | work=[[Calgary Herald]] | first=Laurence | last=Heinen | date=July 5, 2014 | quote=Sutherland doesn't have many more shots to win another title before he turns 65, after which time he's no longer eligible to compete in the Rangeland Derby.}}</ref>  In 2010, Sutherland won the chuckwagon championship for the 11th time, breaking the world record. He was almost 60 years old when he won his final and 12th world championship. He also has a dozen championships from the Calgary Stampede, nine championships from the Ponoka Stampede, and one from his hometown of [[Grande Prairie]].<ref name=\"AlsoRetires\" /> He won his 12th and final world championship not long before his birthday in 2017. The year 2017 was his last year competing, as the event has a mandatory retirement age of 65.<ref name=\":2\" /> Sutherland competed in his last race in Rocky Mountain House in west central Alberta. Sutherland spent 50 years guiding horses around the track.<ref name=\"AlsoRetires\" />\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2012 Calgary Stampede Guy Weadick Award<ref>{{cite web |title=Guy Weadick Award Winners |url=https://www.calgarystampede.com/heritage/guy-weadick-award |website=Calgary Stampede |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n* 12 Calgary Stampede Championships\n* 12 World Championships\n* 7 time Calgary Stampede Aggregate Winner\n* 77 Champion final heats on World Professional Chuckwagon Association Circuit\n* 25 Victories in Championship heats on the World Professional Chuckwagon Association Circuit\n* $300,000 highest bid chuckwagon canvas sold at Calgary Stampede Canvas Auction (2012)\n<small>Source</small>:<ref name=\"Retires\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Alberta Sports Hall of Fame |title=Join us as we welcome the Class of 2020 |url=https://www.todayville.com/join-us-as-we-welcome-the-class-of-2020/ |website=todayville Red Deer |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSutherland owned a country bar in Canada in the 1980s, called Kelly's Bar at the Sutherland Inn, in Clairmont, Alberta.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jepson|first1=Tim|last2=Lee|first2=Phil|last3=Smith|first3=Tania|last4=Williams|first4=Christian|title=The Rough Guide to Canada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=92iMgE8GYQ4C&pg=PA637&lpg=PA637&dq=Kelly%27s+Bar+Clairmont+Alberta.&source=bl&ots=ubtZ70ubkU&sig=jYodKFzBZLx-CjtVoCoRz2kwncA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwitoa2czbHUAhUJLmMKHVbAD-8Q6AEIajAG#v=onepage&q=Kelly%27s%20Bar%20Clairmont%20Alberta.&f=false|website=books.google.com|publisher=Rough Guides|accessdate=9 June 2017|language=en|date=2004}}</ref> His first Chuckwagon hung from the ceiling above the dance floor.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} Sutherland's wife Debbie has been riding with him ever since he began racing competitively.<ref name=\"Retires\" />\n\nIn 2009, Sutherland participated in the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] as one of 13 torchbearers for his home town of Grand Prairie, Alberta.  Each of the torchbearers rode down the main street of the town for the one-kilometre ride with the torch. He revealed that he will put the used torch on display with his 38 chuckwagon trophies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Carrying the Olympic Torch: Day 8 \u2014 Yellowknife to Cold Lake|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/staff-blogs/carrying-the-olympic-torch-day-8-yellowknife-to-cold-lake|website=Vancouver Sun|publisher=www.vancouversun.|accessdate=January 13, 2018|date=7 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sutherland, Kelly}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Rodeo in Canada]]\n[[Category:Rodeo performers]]\n[[Category:People from Grande Prairie]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnleelynn", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add wikiliks.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelly_Sutherland_(chuckwagon)"}
{"title_page": "Niccol\u00f2 Salvietti", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Niccol\u00f2 Salvietti\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1993|11|3|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = {{ct|SAN}}\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = 2016\u2013\n| proteam1       = {{ct|SAN|2016}}\n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n'''Niccol\u00f2 Salvietti''' (born 3 November 1993) is an Italian [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"PCS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=178549 |title=Niccol\u00f2 Salvietti |accessdate=17 September 2017 |work=ProCyclingStats}}</ref> He competed in the [[2017 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's team time trial|men's team time trial]] event at the [[2017 UCI Road World Championships]].<ref name=\"start\">{{cite web |url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/World_Championships_-_TTT_2017_Startlist |title=World Championships - TTT Startlist |accessdate=17 September 2017 |work=ProCyclingStats}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ProCyclingStats|178549}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salvietti, Niccolo}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1990s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Niccol\u00f2 Salvietti\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1993|11|3|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = {{ct|SAN}}\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = 2016\u2013\n| proteam1       = {{ct|SAN|2016}}\n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n'''Niccol\u00f2 Salvietti''' (born 3 November 1993) is an Italian [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"PCS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=178549 |title=Niccol\u00f2 Salvietti |accessdate=17 September 2017 |work=ProCyclingStats}}</ref> He competed in the [[2017 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's team time trial|men's team time trial]] event at the [[2017 UCI Road World Championships]].<ref name=\"start\">{{cite web |url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/World_Championships_-_TTT_2017_Startlist |title=World Championships - TTT Startlist |accessdate=17 September 2017 |work=ProCyclingStats}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ProCyclingStats|178549}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salvietti, Niccolo}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1990s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niccol%C3%B2_Salvietti"}
{"title_page": "Dorayd bin Al Soma", "text_new": "'''Dorayd bin Al Soma''' was a pre-[[Islamic]] [[warrior]], [[knight]] and [[poet]] of the [[Hawazin]] tribe. He was also the chief of the [[Banu Jusham]], or the modern day Al-Qthami clan of the tribe of [[Otaibah]]. Historians have cited that he contributed to more than a hundred battles for his tribe. By the time of the [[rise of Islam]], he was already an old man and remained a [[pagan]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=\u0628\u0646 \u0623\u064a\u0648\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0645\u064a\u0631\u064a|first1=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643 \u0628\u0646 \u0647\u0634\u0627\u0645|title=\u0645\u0642\u062a\u0644 \u062f\u0631\u064a\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0645\u0629|url=http://library.islamweb.net/newlibrary/display_book.php?idfrom=1427&idto=1427&bk_no=58&ID=681}}</ref>\n\nIn his old age, he proposed marriage to the poetess [[Al-Khansa]].  According to the ''[[Kitab al-Aghani]]'', she sent a slave woman to watch him urinate, saying \"If his urine cuts into the ground, he has got something left in him; but if his urine trickles over the surface, there's no zip in him.\"  The slave woman observed only a weak stream of urine, so Al-Khansa refused his offer of marriage.<ref>{{cite book|title=Early Arabic Poetry: Select Poems|last=Jones|first=Alan|publisher=Ithaca Press|year=2011|isbn=9780863723872|page=ix|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CRWNAQAACAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:7th-century Arabic poets]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Hawazin]]\n[[Category:One Thousand and One Nights characters]]\n", "text_old": "'''Dorayd bin Al Soma''' was a pre-[[Islamic]] [[warrior]], [[knight]] and [[poet]] of the [[Hawazin]] tribe. He was also the chief of the [[Banu Jusham]], or the modern day Al-Qthami clan of the tribe of [[Otaibah]]. Historians have cited that he contributed to more than a hundred battles for his tribe. By the time of the [[rise of Islam]], he was already an old man and remained a [[pagan]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=\u0628\u0646 \u0623\u064a\u0648\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0645\u064a\u0631\u064a|first1=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643 \u0628\u0646 \u0647\u0634\u0627\u0645|title=\u0645\u0642\u062a\u0644 \u062f\u0631\u064a\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0645\u0629|url=http://library.islamweb.net/newlibrary/display_book.php?idfrom=1427&idto=1427&bk_no=58&ID=681}}</ref>\n\nIn his old age, he proposed marriage to the poetess [[Al-Khansa]].  According to the ''[[Kitab al-Aghani]]'', she sent a slave woman to watch him urinate, saying \"If his urine cuts into the ground, he has got something left in him; but if his urine trickles over the surface, there's no zip in him.\"  The slave woman observed only a weak stream of urine, so Al-Khansa refused his offer of marriage.<ref>{{cite book|title=Early Arabic Poetry: Select Poems|last=Jones|first=Alan|publisher=Ithaca Press|year=2011|isbn=9780863723872|page=ix|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CRWNAQAACAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:7th-century Arabic poets]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Hawazin]]\n[[Category:One Thousand and One Nights characters]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dorayd_bin_Al_Soma"}
{"title_page": "Niccol\u00f2 Pacinotti", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Niccol\u00f2 Pacinotti\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| fullname       =\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{bda|1995|2|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Florence]], [[Italy]]\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    =\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  = 2014\u20132015\n| amateurteam1   = Mastromarco Sensi Dover Benedetti\n| amateuryears2  = 2016\n| amateurteam2   = Hoppl\u00e0-Petroli Firenze\n| proyears1      = 2017\n| proteam1       = {{ct|CSF|2017}}\n| proyears2      =\n| proteam2       =\n| majorwins      =\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n}}\n'''Niccolo Pacinotti''' (born 5 February 1995 in [[Florence]]) is an Italian cyclist, who last competed for [[UCI Professional Continental]] team {{ct|BRD|2017}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bardianicsf.com/en/news/diciassette-corridori-per-la-nuova-stagione/|title=Seventeen riders in 2018 roster|work={{ct|BRD|2017}}|publisher=GM Sport SRL|date=14 November 2017|accessdate=23 January 2018|quote=Referred to 2017 roster, the team also notified the rescission of the contract by mutual consent with riders Nicola Boem and Niccol\u00f2 Pacinotti.}}</ref>\n\nHe won the Hoppl\u00e0 Petroli Firenze in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Niccol\u00f2 Pacinotti \u00e8 il terzo neoprofessionista della Bardiani CSF - Cicloweb|url=http://www.cicloweb.it/2016/08/17/niccolo-pacinotti-e-il-terzo-neoprofessionista-della-bardiani-csf/|website=Cicloweb|accessdate=24 October 2017|language=it-IT|date=17 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=I Volti Nuovi del Gruppo, Niccol\u00f2 Pacinotti: \"Il professionismo \u00e8 tutta un'altra cosa\" {{!}} SpazioCiclismo|url=http://cyclingpro.net/spaziociclismo/esclusive/volti-nuovi-del-gruppo-niccolo-pacinotti-professionismo-tutta-altra-cosa/|website=cyclingpro.net|accessdate=24 October 2017|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Niccol\u00f2 Pacinotti \u2013 Bardiani CSF|url=http://www.cykelnmagazine.com/niccolo-pacinotti-bardiani-csf/|website=www.cykelnmagazine.com|accessdate=24 October 2017|language=it-IT}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n;2012\n: 1st Trofeo Buffoni\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{procyclingstats}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pacinotti, Niccolo}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Florence]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1990s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Niccol\u00f2 Pacinotti\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| fullname       =\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{bda|1995|2|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Florence]], [[Italy]]\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    =\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  = 2014\u20132015\n| amateurteam1   = Mastromarco Sensi Dover Benedetti\n| amateuryears2  = 2016\n| amateurteam2   = Hoppl\u00e0-Petroli Firenze\n| proyears1      = 2017\n| proteam1       = {{ct|CSF|2017}}\n| proyears2      =\n| proteam2       =\n| majorwins      =\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n}}\n'''Niccolo Pacinotti''' (born 5 February 1995 in [[Florence]]) is an Italian cyclist, who last competed for [[UCI Professional Continental]] team {{ct|BRD|2017}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bardianicsf.com/en/news/diciassette-corridori-per-la-nuova-stagione/|title=Seventeen riders in 2018 roster|work={{ct|BRD|2017}}|publisher=GM Sport SRL|date=14 November 2017|accessdate=23 January 2018|quote=Referred to 2017 roster, the team also notified the rescission of the contract by mutual consent with riders Nicola Boem and Niccol\u00f2 Pacinotti.}}</ref>\n\nHe won the Hoppl\u00e0 Petroli Firenze in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Niccol\u00f2 Pacinotti \u00e8 il terzo neoprofessionista della Bardiani CSF - Cicloweb|url=http://www.cicloweb.it/2016/08/17/niccolo-pacinotti-e-il-terzo-neoprofessionista-della-bardiani-csf/|website=Cicloweb|accessdate=24 October 2017|language=it-IT|date=17 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=I Volti Nuovi del Gruppo, Niccol\u00f2 Pacinotti: \"Il professionismo \u00e8 tutta un'altra cosa\" {{!}} SpazioCiclismo|url=http://cyclingpro.net/spaziociclismo/esclusive/volti-nuovi-del-gruppo-niccolo-pacinotti-professionismo-tutta-altra-cosa/|website=cyclingpro.net|accessdate=24 October 2017|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Niccol\u00f2 Pacinotti \u2013 Bardiani CSF|url=http://www.cykelnmagazine.com/niccolo-pacinotti-bardiani-csf/|website=www.cykelnmagazine.com|accessdate=24 October 2017|language=it-IT}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n;2012\n: 1st Trofeo Buffoni\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{procyclingstats}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pacinotti, Niccolo}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Florence]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1990s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niccol%C3%B2_Pacinotti"}
{"title_page": "Lauma", "text_new": "{{Baltic religion}}\n[[File:Romas Venckus \u201eLaum\u0117 Geroji ragana\u201c.jpg|250px|thumb|right|\"Lauma/The Good Witch\", 1980 wooden sculpture by Romas Venckus at the [[Hill of Witches]]]]\n[[Latvian language|Latvian]]: '''Lauma''', [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]: '''Laum\u0117''' is a woodland [[Fairy|fae]], and guardian spirit of [[orphans]] in Eastern [[Baltic mythology]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lauma|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/332311/lauma|website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Inc|accessdate=11 March 2013}}</ref> Originally a sky spirit, her compassion for human suffering brought her to earth to share our fate.<ref name=TWO/>\n\n==In Lithuanian mythology==\n\nLaum\u0117s are the very oldest goddesses of [[Lithuanian mythology]]. The image of these goddesses may have formed during the historical [[Mesolithic]] period, just after the [[Ice Age]].<ref name=TWO/> \nLaum\u0117s could appear in the form of animals, as mares or as female goats, bears and dogs. Later, Laum\u0117s had an [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] appearance: they usually had birds\u2019 claws for feet and appeared as women with the head or lower body of a female goat.  Other forms included half-human/half dog or half mare, similar to [[centaurs]].  Like [[cyclops]], Laum\u0117s often had only one eye. They also had large breasts with stone nipples; pieces of [[belemnitida]] found on the ground were called \"Laum\u0117s nipples.\"<ref name=ONE>Laum\u0117. Mitologijos enciklopedija, 2 tomas. \u2013 Vilnius: Vaga, 1999. \u2013 283 p.</ref>\n\nLaum\u0117s were dangerous, especially to men. They could tickle or [[Pinch (action)|tweak]] them to death and then eat their bodies, and in this way, they were similar to Lamia of [[Greek mythology]]. The Lithuanian myth also claimed Laum\u0117s kept huge cows which could be milked by all people. However, after very cold weathers, the cows died; pieces of belemnitida were considered to be the remains of their [[udder]]s.  Laum\u0117s were afraid of tools made from [[iron]].<ref name=ONE/>\n\nLaum\u0117s can be considered as atmospheric goddesses. It is said that Laum\u0117 was a beautiful goddess, who lived in clouds and had a diamond throne. Some myths claimed Laum\u0117 was a bride of thunder god [[Perk\u016bnas]]; however, they did not marry because Laum\u0117 fell in love with the Moon, who was considered a male god in Lithuania.  In other stories, the bride was stolen by the devil Velnias, named Tuolius. That's why Laum\u0117 liked moonshine. In other myth, the bride of Perk\u016bnas was a Laum\u0117 called [[Vaiva]]. The rainbow was called the ribbon of Vaiva. Despite her marriage, she had a beloved singer named Straublys. Straublys had stolen the ribbon of Vaiva. During the rain, Straublys stretches the ribbon of Vaiva across the sky, while Perk\u016bnas is angry and shouts in thunder.<ref name=ONE/> It was believed it is the rainbow that causes the rain, while Lithuanian shepherds had a prayer or curse by which the rainbow had to turn to pieces and make the rain go away. The other myth claimed Laum\u0117 fell in love with a beautiful young man down to earth. They both had a son named Meilius (name derived from word 'Meil\u0117' - love). Laum\u0117 descended to the sky to feed her son with her breasts from time to time. However, the highest God found out about the son of sacrilegious love, smashed him into the highest place of the sky and gave him a place between stars. After that he cut Laum\u0117s breasts, and so, stone pieces of it can be found on Earth.\n\nLaum\u0117s descended from the sky to Earth. They lived nearby lakes, abandoned bath-houses, in islands of lakes or dense forests. Lots of names of water pools in Lithuania are named after the word Laum\u0117. Laum\u0117s liked to gather near rivers, lakes, swamps, in meadows, there dew fell in the night in New Moon or [[Full Moon]]. They danced and enjoyed themselves, leaving circles (like [[Fairy Ring]]) in the grass. Usually, Laum\u0117s were most powerful at Friday of [[New Moon]], at the rainiest days of the month in Lithuania. Laum\u0117s could cause hail, storm or rain by singing, dancing or by curses. Laum\u0117s song was traditionally performed during weddings up until the 19th century. The song was performed by girls dancing in a circle, with one in the middle. The dance and song was also said to cause rain.<ref>An encyclopedic dictionary of mythological and folkloric characters, epics, legends, etc. of most nations of the world, with particular attention to nations of the USSR. Edited by E.M. Meletinskii, S.S. Averintsev, V.V. Ivanov, R.V. Makarevich, et al. 1990. {{ISBN|9785852700322}}</ref>\n\nLater on, Laum\u0117s were depicted as very beautiful women, who appeared both naked or wearing very fine clothing. The [[Rainbow]] was often called a ribbon lost by Laum\u0117s. What's how they were associated with weaving. Laum\u0117s usually appeared in groups of three. They were able to do women\u2019s work perfectly, as are especially skilled in weaving and spinning. They love children, respect industriousness and help those in need. They punish those who ridicule them, and those who are lazy. Following are two examples [[Folklore|folk tale]]s featuring Laum\u0117s:<ref name=TWO>Of Gods and Men: Studies in Lithuanian Mythology (Folklore Studies in Translation), Algirdas J. Greimas (1992) 248 pag. {{ISBN|9780253326522}}, {{ISBN|978-0253326522}}</ref>\n\n===Laum\u0117s (fairies) and the baby===\nA woman was harvesting a flower bed and had taken her child with her. She was so busy with her work that the child slept the day through, and she left the little one behind.<ref> Ilze Vjatere. Mitolo\u0123ijas v\u0101rdn\u012bca. R\u012bga : Avots, 2004. 190. lpp. {{ISBN|978-9-98-475736-0}}</ref>\n\nThe woman went home at the end of the day to milk the cows and make dinner. She served her husband, who asked her \"Where\u2019s my son?\" With terror, she whispered, \"I have forgotten him!\" She ran as fast as she could to the place in which she left her son, hearing a Laum\u00e9 speak: \"[[\u010ci\u016b\u010dia li\u016blia]], forgotten child.\" The mother, from the distance, asked the Laume for her child back. The fairie said, \"Come, come, dear woman, take your child, we have done nothing to him. We know that you work very hard, at many jobs, and that you didn\u2019t want to leave your child behind.\"\n\nThe fairies then went on to shower the babe with much treasure, enough gifts to raise several children upon. The mother went home with her precious baby and with her gifts; she was greeted with great joy.\n\nAnother woman, hearing of her good fortune, was taken over by jealousy. She took to thinking, \"I shall do the same as her, and also be showered in gifts.\" The next evening, at dusk, she took her child, left him in the fields and went home. She ate dinner, thoughtlessly, before pausing to think of her child\u2014and the treasure.\n\nWhen she approached the field, she heard the fairies, \"[[\u010ci\u016b\u010dia li\u016blia]], you left your child in greed.\" And the child screamed with such great pain, for he was pinched and tortured mercilessly. They continued their torture until the mother came. The fairies tossed the child at her feet. The babe was dead.\n\n===The Fairies foretell a newborn's future===\n\nA Laum\u0117 would come to a window and would yell, \"Hundreds born, hundreds died, what of his fate?\" Another would answer back, \"Birth at night, death at night.\" And again they would yell and moan at the window. From within another would answer, \"This nightly birth is a big work smarter not harder, to live well whole life long.\" Again, yelling at the window, \"Hundreds born, hundreds dead, what of his fate?\u201d Another answer: \"Morning time born will be a strong worker\". And again, after some time, begins the same questioning. The answer was \"Noontime born is a very happy child, full of bubbles and envy for what is not strictly in accordance with wealth.\"\n\n==In Latvian mythology==\nIn [[Latvian mythology]] Lauma is an assistant at birth, assuring the health and welfare of both mother and child. If the mother does not survive or gives the child up, she takes on the role of spiritual foster mother for the child. She spins the cloth of life for the child but weeps at the fate of some. The fact that the cloth can, to a degree, weave itself, indicates a higher power than Lauma.<ref>Jonas Balys, Haralds Biezais: Baltische Mythologie. In: Hans Wilhelm Haussig, Jonas Balys (Hrsg.): G\u00f6tter und Mythen im Alten Europa (= W\u00f6rterbuch der Mythologie. Abteilung 1: Die alten Kulturv\u00f6lker. Band 2). Klett-Cotta, Stuttgart 1973, {{ISBN|3-12-909820-8}}.</ref>\n\nOver the years, her image has gradually degraded. Accused of baby-snatching by disrespectful husbands (since she is unable to bear children of her own), her looks and sweetness were lost, turning her into an evil old [[hag]]. She weeps at her destined fate, hoping for the day when she will return to her former beautiful self.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Time in religion and mythology}}\n\n[[Category:Lithuanian folklore characters]]\n[[Category:Fortune goddesses]]\n[[Category:Latvian goddesses]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian goddesses]]\n[[Category:Time and fate goddesses]]\n[[Category:Tree goddesses]]\n[[Category:Textiles in mythology and folklore]]\n[[Category:Female legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Baltic legendary creatures]]\n", "text_old": "{{Baltic religion}}\n[[File:Juodkrante - panoramio (1).jpg|250px|thumb|right|\"Lauma/The Good Witch\", 1980 wooden sculpture by Romas Venckus at the [[Hill of Witches]]]]\n[[Latvian language|Latvian]]: '''Lauma''', [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]: '''Laum\u0117''' is a woodland [[Fairy|fae]], and guardian spirit of [[orphans]] in Eastern [[Baltic mythology]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lauma|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/332311/lauma|website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Inc|accessdate=11 March 2013}}</ref> Originally a sky spirit, her compassion for human suffering brought her to earth to share our fate.<ref name=TWO/>\n\n==In Lithuanian mythology==\n\nLaum\u0117s are the very oldest goddesses of [[Lithuanian mythology]]. The image of these goddesses may have formed during the historical [[Mesolithic]] period, just after the [[Ice Age]].<ref name=TWO/> \nLaum\u0117s could appear in the form of animals, as mares or as female goats, bears and dogs. Later, Laum\u0117s had an [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] appearance: they usually had birds\u2019 claws for feet and appeared as women with the head or lower body of a female goat.  Other forms included half-human/half dog or half mare, similar to [[centaurs]].  Like [[cyclops]], Laum\u0117s often had only one eye. They also had large breasts with stone nipples; pieces of [[belemnitida]] found on the ground were called \"Laum\u0117s nipples.\"<ref name=ONE>Laum\u0117. Mitologijos enciklopedija, 2 tomas. \u2013 Vilnius: Vaga, 1999. \u2013 283 p.</ref>\n\nLaum\u0117s were dangerous, especially to men. They could tickle or [[Pinch (action)|tweak]] them to death and then eat their bodies, and in this way, they were similar to Lamia of [[Greek mythology]]. The Lithuanian myth also claimed Laum\u0117s kept huge cows which could be milked by all people. However, after very cold weathers, the cows died; pieces of belemnitida were considered to be the remains of their [[udder]]s.  Laum\u0117s were afraid of tools made from [[iron]].<ref name=ONE/>\n\nLaum\u0117s can be considered as atmospheric goddesses. It is said that Laum\u0117 was a beautiful goddess, who lived in clouds and had a diamond throne. Some myths claimed Laum\u0117 was a bride of thunder god [[Perk\u016bnas]]; however, they did not marry because Laum\u0117 fell in love with the Moon, who was considered a male god in Lithuania.  In other stories, the bride was stolen by the devil Velnias, named Tuolius. That's why Laum\u0117 liked moonshine. In other myth, the bride of Perk\u016bnas was a Laum\u0117 called [[Vaiva]]. The rainbow was called the ribbon of Vaiva. Despite her marriage, she had a beloved singer named Straublys. Straublys had stolen the ribbon of Vaiva. During the rain, Straublys stretches the ribbon of Vaiva across the sky, while Perk\u016bnas is angry and shouts in thunder.<ref name=ONE/> It was believed it is the rainbow that causes the rain, while Lithuanian shepherds had a prayer or curse by which the rainbow had to turn to pieces and make the rain go away. The other myth claimed Laum\u0117 fell in love with a beautiful young man down to earth. They both had a son named Meilius (name derived from word 'Meil\u0117' - love). Laum\u0117 descended to the sky to feed her son with her breasts from time to time. However, the highest God found out about the son of sacrilegious love, smashed him into the highest place of the sky and gave him a place between stars. After that he cut Laum\u0117s breasts, and so, stone pieces of it can be found on Earth.\n\nLaum\u0117s descended from the sky to Earth. They lived nearby lakes, abandoned bath-houses, in islands of lakes or dense forests. Lots of names of water pools in Lithuania are named after the word Laum\u0117. Laum\u0117s liked to gather near rivers, lakes, swamps, in meadows, there dew fell in the night in New Moon or [[Full Moon]]. They danced and enjoyed themselves, leaving circles (like [[Fairy Ring]]) in the grass. Usually, Laum\u0117s were most powerful at Friday of [[New Moon]], at the rainiest days of the month in Lithuania. Laum\u0117s could cause hail, storm or rain by singing, dancing or by curses. Laum\u0117s song was traditionally performed during weddings up until the 19th century. The song was performed by girls dancing in a circle, with one in the middle. The dance and song was also said to cause rain.<ref>An encyclopedic dictionary of mythological and folkloric characters, epics, legends, etc. of most nations of the world, with particular attention to nations of the USSR. Edited by E.M. Meletinskii, S.S. Averintsev, V.V. Ivanov, R.V. Makarevich, et al. 1990. {{ISBN|9785852700322}}</ref>\n\nLater on, Laum\u0117s were depicted as very beautiful women, who appeared both naked or wearing very fine clothing. The [[Rainbow]] was often called a ribbon lost by Laum\u0117s. What's how they were associated with weaving. Laum\u0117s usually appeared in groups of three. They were able to do women\u2019s work perfectly, as are especially skilled in weaving and spinning. They love children, respect industriousness and help those in need. They punish those who ridicule them, and those who are lazy. Following are two examples [[Folklore|folk tale]]s featuring Laum\u0117s:<ref name=TWO>Of Gods and Men: Studies in Lithuanian Mythology (Folklore Studies in Translation), Algirdas J. Greimas (1992) 248 pag. {{ISBN|9780253326522}}, {{ISBN|978-0253326522}}</ref>\n\n===Laum\u0117s (fairies) and the baby===\nA woman was harvesting a flower bed and had taken her child with her. She was so busy with her work that the child slept the day through, and she left the little one behind.<ref> Ilze Vjatere. Mitolo\u0123ijas v\u0101rdn\u012bca. R\u012bga : Avots, 2004. 190. lpp. {{ISBN|978-9-98-475736-0}}</ref>\n\nThe woman went home at the end of the day to milk the cows and make dinner. She served her husband, who asked her \"Where\u2019s my son?\" With terror, she whispered, \"I have forgotten him!\" She ran as fast as she could to the place in which she left her son, hearing a Laum\u00e9 speak: \"[[\u010ci\u016b\u010dia li\u016blia]], forgotten child.\" The mother, from the distance, asked the Laume for her child back. The fairie said, \"Come, come, dear woman, take your child, we have done nothing to him. We know that you work very hard, at many jobs, and that you didn\u2019t want to leave your child behind.\"\n\nThe fairies then went on to shower the babe with much treasure, enough gifts to raise several children upon. The mother went home with her precious baby and with her gifts; she was greeted with great joy.\n\nAnother woman, hearing of her good fortune, was taken over by jealousy. She took to thinking, \"I shall do the same as her, and also be showered in gifts.\" The next evening, at dusk, she took her child, left him in the fields and went home. She ate dinner, thoughtlessly, before pausing to think of her child\u2014and the treasure.\n\nWhen she approached the field, she heard the fairies, \"[[\u010ci\u016b\u010dia li\u016blia]], you left your child in greed.\" And the child screamed with such great pain, for he was pinched and tortured mercilessly. They continued their torture until the mother came. The fairies tossed the child at her feet. The babe was dead.\n\n===The Fairies foretell a newborn's future===\n\nA Laum\u0117 would come to a window and would yell, \"Hundreds born, hundreds died, what of his fate?\" Another would answer back, \"Birth at night, death at night.\" And again they would yell and moan at the window. From within another would answer, \"This nightly birth is a big work smarter not harder, to live well whole life long.\" Again, yelling at the window, \"Hundreds born, hundreds dead, what of his fate?\u201d Another answer: \"Morning time born will be a strong worker\". And again, after some time, begins the same questioning. The answer was \"Noontime born is a very happy child, full of bubbles and envy for what is not strictly in accordance with wealth.\"\n\n==In Latvian mythology==\nIn [[Latvian mythology]] Lauma is an assistant at birth, assuring the health and welfare of both mother and child. If the mother does not survive or gives the child up, she takes on the role of spiritual foster mother for the child. She spins the cloth of life for the child but weeps at the fate of some. The fact that the cloth can, to a degree, weave itself, indicates a higher power than Lauma.<ref>Jonas Balys, Haralds Biezais: Baltische Mythologie. In: Hans Wilhelm Haussig, Jonas Balys (Hrsg.): G\u00f6tter und Mythen im Alten Europa (= W\u00f6rterbuch der Mythologie. Abteilung 1: Die alten Kulturv\u00f6lker. Band 2). Klett-Cotta, Stuttgart 1973, {{ISBN|3-12-909820-8}}.</ref>\n\nOver the years, her image has gradually degraded. Accused of baby-snatching by disrespectful husbands (since she is unable to bear children of her own), her looks and sweetness were lost, turning her into an evil old [[hag]]. She weeps at her destined fate, hoping for the day when she will return to her former beautiful self.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Time in religion and mythology}}\n\n[[Category:Lithuanian folklore characters]]\n[[Category:Fortune goddesses]]\n[[Category:Latvian goddesses]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian goddesses]]\n[[Category:Time and fate goddesses]]\n[[Category:Tree goddesses]]\n[[Category:Textiles in mythology and folklore]]\n[[Category:Female legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Baltic legendary creatures]]\n", "name_user": "Fridolin freudenfett", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Juodkrante - panoramio (1).jpg\u2192File:Romas Venckus \u201eLaum\u0117 Geroji ragana\u201c.jpgCriterion 2(meaningless or ambiguous name)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lauma"}
